Three medics believed to have facilitated the escape of 80 patients from Mathari Teaching and Referral Hospital in June last year during a strike by doctors and nurses have been charged with negligence.Isaac Maina, Jacqueline Aloo and Jacklyne Obonyo yesterday denied unlocking padlocks at the mental hospital to let the patients escape on June 16, 2016.The three were accused of being reckless and facilitating the escape of 81 men mental patients in wards eight and nine. At the time, nurses had called a strike pushing for better pay and working conditions. The striking nurses were demanding the implementation of a collective bargaining agreement and had threatened to disrupt operations in all major hospitals. They were each released on Sh200,000 bail. The case will be mentioned on July 9.